Issues.Body:
Hello, thank you for the great framework!

I would like to suggest an improvement regarding the dark mode feature in Bulma.

Currently, dark mode styles are included in the build by default. It would be helpful if we could optionally disable dark mode when compiling Bulma via SASS.

## Suggestion:
Introduce a configuration variable such as $enable-dark-mode in initial-variables with !default: true

Structure the dark mode-related styles to be included conditionally based on this variable

This way, users who do not need dark mode support can compile a lighter CSS file

```
$enable-dark-mode: true !default;

// prefers-color-scheme: dark
@if $enable-dark-mode{
  @include cv.system-theme($name: "dark") {
    @include dark.dark-theme;
  }
}

//[data-theme=dark], .theme-dark
@if $enable-dark-mode{
  @include cv.bulma-theme($name: "dark") {
    @include dark.dark-theme;
    @include setup.setup-theme;
  }
}
```

This approach would provide flexibility and reduce the CSS output size for users not using dark mode.
Thanks for considering this enhancement!

## Description

Hi, I noticed that nested ul in content block look kind of strange. 

> [!NOTE]
> In the bottom right corner of the images is the html element and its
> css rules.

## Actual Behavior

When I inspect the rules, I can see that this rule has precendence.

    .content ul:not(:first-child) {
        margin-top: 1em;
    }

![wrong](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/60de00d0-3b48-4f13-b111-58bbc767a3eb)

## Expected Behavior

There is another rule that seems actually reasonable. If I deactive
above rule, it takes action.

    .content ul ul {
        list-style-type: circle;
        margin-bottom: .25em;
        margin-top: .25em;
    }

![right](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/4968be5b-4024-4c66-ac76-5e64ff0a434f)
